Certainly! Here’s a simple JavaScript function that takes a JSON array of objects and generates an HTML table as a string. You can then insert this HTML into a `<table>` element on your page.

### Function: `jsonToTable`

```javascript
function jsonToTable(data) {
    // Start building the HTML table as a string
    let html = "<table border='1'>";

    // Header row
    html += "<tr>";
    for (let key of Object.keys(data[0])) { // Assumes all objects have the same keys
        html += `<th>${key}</th>`;
    }
    html += "</tr>";

    // Data rows
    for (let item of data) {
        html += "<tr>";
        for (let key of Object.keys(item)) {
            html += `<td>${item[key]}</td>`;
        }
        html += "</tr>";
    }

    html += "</table>";
    return html;
}
```

---

### How to Use

Suppose you have this JSON array:

```json
[
  { "name": "Alice", "age": 30, "city": "New York" },
  { "name": "Bob",   "age": 25, "city": "Chicago" }
]
```

**In JavaScript:**

```javascript
const data = [
  { "name": "Alice", "age": 30, "city": "New York" },
  { "name": "Bob",   "age": 25, "city": "Chicago" }
];

// Get the HTML table string
const tableHtml = jsonToTable(data);

// Insert into the body of a div, for example:
document.body.insertAdjacentHTML("beforeend", tableHtml);
```

---

### Notes

- **Key Order:** The order of columns in the table will follow the order of keys in `Object.keys(data[0])`, which for modern JS is insertion order (if your objects were created that way).
- **Dynamic Keys:** If your objects might have different keys, you may want to collect all unique keys first.
- **Table Rendering in DOM:** Alternatively, you can build a `<table>` element in DOM instead of returning a string if you prefer a more interactive approach.

